replies.bodyText:
I added a unit test, and it was indeed removing the entries because of the way the test code works, but would not have done so in production.
This code, in ConfigMapHelper.IntrospectionConfigMapStep
    public NextAction apply(Packet packet) {
      IntrospectionLoader loader = new IntrospectionLoader(packet, this);
      if (loader.isTopologyNotValid()) {
        return doNext(reportTopologyErrorsAndStop(), packet);
      } else if (loader.getDomainConfig() == null)  {  // <-- short-circuit
        return doNext(loader.createIntrospectionVersionUpdateStep(), packet);
      } else {
        LOGGER.fine(MessageKeys.WLS_CONFIGURATION_READ, timeSinceJobStart(packet), loader.getDomainConfig());
        loader.updatePacket();
        return doNext(loader.createValidationStep(), packet);
      }
    }

detects the short-circuit case in the second branch, and creates a step that only patches a label. Thus, it wouldn't change any of the entries; however, since the local copy in the configmap steps was actually the same instance as the simulated configmap, it was causing the test to fail. I have fixed that by not updating the local copy in the patch-only case, but I should really fix the simulated Kubernetes. This isn't the first time I've had trouble testing a complex case.
